            "id": "0c949d3c5e4f4f399d0ee",
            "questionText": "A transformer in a power distribution system has a primary coil with 500 turns and is connected to an alternating voltage source of 120 V. The magnetic flux in the core changes at a rate of 0.05 Weber/second, and the transformer is designed to output 2400 V with 95% efficiency. Assuming a primary current of 2 A, determine the secondary current.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "6c5dd60eb23542b18e451",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula to compute the input power from the primary voltage and current. Which one of the following formulas relates voltage ($!$V$!$), current ($!$I$!$), and power ($!$P$!$)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P = V \\times I$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P = \\frac{V}{I}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P = V + I$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "3296230c114c404997443",
                    "stepText": "Now, use the formula you selected to calculate the primary input power. Given that the voltage is $!$120\\,V$!$ and the current is $!$2\\,A$!$, what is the input power?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "240"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "W",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "7233443585d1440490a94",
                    "stepText": "Next, let's identify the formula that relates the efficiency of a transformer to its input and output power. Which formula correctly applies the efficiency to determine the output power?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P_{out} = \\text{efficiency} \\times P_{in}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P_{out} = \\frac{P_{in}}{\\text{efficiency}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P_{out} = P_{in} - \\text{efficiency}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "9b2aca1688c648e5b2453",
                    "stepText": "Now, apply the efficiency to compute the usable output power. Given that the primary input power is $!$240\\,W$!$ and the transformer has an efficiency of $!$95\\%$!$, what is the output power?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "228"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "W",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "cdf5211f73c04b96a5fbb",
                    "stepText": "Now, let's choose the correct formula that relates power, voltage, and current for determining the secondary current. Which of the following options is the appropriate formula?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{P}{V}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = P \\times V$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{V}{P}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "7afe613b71cf4c36a0268",
                    "stepText": "Finally, calculate the secondary current. With the output power at $!$228\\,W$!$ and the secondary voltage at $!$2400\\,V$!$, what is the current in the secondary coil?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.095"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "A",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "35a96ae3ff264b96981f5",
            "questionText": "A train is traveling at a constant speed of $!$30 m/s$!$ on a track that runs perpendicular to a uniform magnetic field of $!$0.5 T$!$. The axle connecting the wheels is $!$1.5 m$!$ long. Determine the magnitude of the electric field experienced by the electrons in the axle.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "d5c75bfa152b4e018c20e",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula that gives the induced electromotive force (EMF) when a conductor moves through a magnetic field. Which one of the following formulas represents that concept?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "70734415-23ea-4f42-9d80-7b51cd1cf9e6"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\epsilon = BvL$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\epsilon = B+v+L$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\epsilon = \\frac{v}{BL}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\epsilon = B^2vL^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "6c21109e4fdb44cf8678f",
                    "stepText": "Now that we've identified the proper formula for motional EMF, use it along with the given values: magnetic field $!$B = 0.5 T$!$, speed $!$v = 30 m/s$!$, and length $!$L = 1.5 m$!$. Compute the induced EMF. What is the numerical value for the induced EMF?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "22.5"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "V",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "70734415-23ea-4f42-9d80-7b51cd1cf9e6"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "a359957677ed41f98da8b",
                    "stepText": "Next, think about how the electric field in the axle is related to the induced EMF. Which of the following relationships correctly connects the electric field $!$E$!$ with the induced EMF $!$\\epsilon$!$ and the length $!$L$!$ of the conductor?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E = \\epsilon /L$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E = \\epsilon \\cdot L$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E = L/\\epsilon$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E = \\epsilon - L$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "33a1f76b3c6d4284a890f",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the induced EMF calculated in the previous step and the axle length provided, compute the magnitude of the electric field experienced by the electrons. What is the value of this electric field?",
                    "stepText2": "",
